December 10, 2011: Hello and welcome to our coverage of the second day of the second Test in Hobart. An early start today to make up for the time lost to rain and bad light yesterday. Australia are one down, Phil Hughes is gone. Martin runs in, bowling to Warner. Three slips, two gullys. It's Martin's birthday

5.20pm Play has been called off for the day. It's a shame because the cricket we did get to see was exciting, only to be cut short by rain and bad light. Let's hope play tomorrow isn't affected by the weather. Given the way things panned out on the field today, it looks like we have a good game in store. Join us tomorrow, and many thanks for sending your feedback. Please do keep them coming. You could read Dan Brettig's report for the day's play before signing off. See you again tomorrow, we'll have an early start to compensate for the time lost to rain today. Join us at 10am Hobart time, cheers.

The scheduled close of play is 5.30pm. Seems unlikely we'll get any play today.

Simon: "People always say that batsmen have nothing to gain from these situations, batting for 5 - 10 overs. But I'm not buying it! Firstly, there are runs. Not letting the bowlers take wickets, frustrating the opposing team, showing determination and focus. Surely if Warner and Khawaja can go out there and stay out there for 5 - 10 overs they will gain a lot!"

5.00pm Bad news again. Brydon: Covers back on. Just a light sprinkling of rain again, but this late in the day it could be fatal.

Tom: "Given Watson and Marsh are set to be back Boxing day, you would have to think they would both come in for Hughes and possibly Warner unless he does something to secure his place. Khawaja and Marsh can both open and bat at 3rd so there really is no reason for Hughes to stay in the team given his feeble performances."

4.45pm There will be an official inspection at 5pm. A decision will be taken then.

Miles: "@Nick. Cowan has been playing well lately yes but before those 3 centuries were 7 scores the best of which was 25. If shield cricket was a deciding factor hughes would never leave but i do agree he needs a spell out of the national team. Love to see him back in 2-3 years with a bit more experience and maturity, remember he is only 23."

4.35pm: The covers are coming off now. It all depends on how long it will take to get the outfield ready.

4.30pm: Update from Brydon: The rain does seem to have stopped and the umpires are wandering out to have a look at the ground

Plenty of puddles on the covers though, hard to imagine that with stumps an hour away they will get back on.

Rastawookie: "@Wilfred. Wade is a quality bat, but his glovework is no better than Haddin's, I think we wait for Paine who is a far superior gloveman to both Wade and Haddin, and is more than useful with the bat."

Nick: "Whilst the selectors are right to give players an adequate chance to establish themselves, I think Hughes has gone past that point. They need to replace him with someone who can anchor an end, bide their time, but still score strongly - for example, Ed Cowan who is playing this role with aplomb for Tasmania." Three centuries on the trot for Cowan in the Shield.

Fuzwald: "Yes, from my office window I can see the rain is falling heavier than the NZ wickets today. Though I don't mind if play stops here, as that means I can see some Aussie batting tomorrow at the ground! As for Hughes... He will have to put in a massive score in the second innings to even have a chance of staying in the team. May already be a lost cause. Marsh or Watson to slot straight in?"

James: "Phil Hughes is picked as an opener, not a middle order batsmen. If he can't hack it at the top, put someone in there who can, lets not nurse someone through who isn't up to it."

4.15pm: It's bucketing down in Hobart, says Brydon. Chances of any more play in the day look pretty bleak.

Wilfred Smallhorn: " think they should give Matthew Wade an opportunity to open the batting. Haddin has hardly been brilliant and is getting on a bit. It would be good chance to get another youngster into the team. Also opens the door for another middle order batsman or even moving Hughes down the order to see if he can find some form against the old ball."

4.05pm: It's still raining in Hobart and is quite gloomy. Prospects of a resumption, not very encouraging.

Meanwhile, in Chittagong, Bangladesh are going strong at 30 for 4.

Jonathan Nicholls: "One point that shouldn't be missed as fans all over NZ bemoan the awful batting: Chris Martin was viewed as being past it at the age of 36, but he's bowling well - four wickets in the first test, and already picked up one here. A triumph for experience! He still can't bat though ..."

I know many of you had enough of limericks but here's the last one Joel: "There was a young batsman named Hughes, what to leave he did struggle to choose. Now he's in a deep trough, playing well outside off, and I think that his test spot he'll lose."

Benny: "Been a supporter of Hughes but he obviously has to go, he has been detrimental to the side for a little too long now, he could well be something special but not right now. At 23 he is something more than handy to have around if he keeps working." Well, he potentially has one more chance.

Melon: "Can't help but wonder how much of a nightmare Shane Bond would have been in these conditions. As much as we miss a top 3, we also miss a genuine strike bowling seamer."

4pm There's a bit of rain in the air and the light isn't great either. The covers are coming on.
